
Overview

BloodHound is one of the main tools I use during post-enumeration in an Active Directory environment.
After getting valid domain credentials, this tool helps map relationships between:

Users

Groups

Computers

Sessions

ACLs / delegated rights

Local admin rights

Attack paths to privileged accounts

Instead of manually reading raw LDAP data, BloodHound turns AD relationships into a graph so it is easier to identify:

Privilege escalation paths

Misconfigured permissions

High-value targets

Lateral movement opportunities

Shortest path to Domain Admin

Tool

BloodHound

bloodhound-python (Linux collector)

SharpHound (Windows collector)

Neo4j (backend database)

Lab Context (Public Safe)

Domain: LAB.local

Collector Host: Kali Linux

Target: Domain Controller / AD environment

Credential Type: Valid domain user or privileged lab account

Network: Internal lab network only

Install / Verify
Check if bloodhound-python is installed
which bloodhound-python
If not installed
sudo apt update
sudo apt install bloodhound -y

Depending on Kali version, package names can vary.
If bloodhound-python is missing, verify package contents:

dpkg -L bloodhound | grep python
Help menu
bloodhound-python -h
Neo4j Setup

BloodHound uses Neo4j as the graph database.

Start Neo4j
sudo neo4j start
Check status
sudo neo4j status
Stop Neo4j
sudo neo4j stop
Default local access

Neo4j web console usually runs on:

http://127.0.0.1:7474

BloodHound app connects to:

bolt://127.0.0.1:7687

Start BloodHound GUI
Launch BloodHound
bloodhound

If the command doesn’t launch:

which bloodhound
Main Collection Command (Linux)
Full collection with DNS server specified
bloodhound-python -u '<USERNAME>' -p '<PASSWORD>' -d LAB.local -ns <DC_IP> -c All
Example public-safe format
bloodhound-python -u 'labuser' -p '<REDACTED_PASSWORD>' -d LAB.local -ns <DC_IP> -c All

This is the main Linux collection command I use most often.

Recommended Output Folder
Create organized output folder
mkdir -p bloodhound-output
Run collection from inside the folder
cd bloodhound-output
bloodhound-python -u 'labuser' -p '<REDACTED_PASSWORD>' -d LAB.local -ns <DC_IP> -c All
Common Collection Methods
Collect everything
bloodhound-python -u 'labuser' -p '<REDACTED_PASSWORD>' -d LAB.local -ns <DC_IP> -c All
Session data only
bloodhound-python -u 'labuser' -p '<REDACTED_PASSWORD>' -d LAB.local -ns <DC_IP> -c Session
Group memberships only
bloodhound-python -u 'labuser' -p '<REDACTED_PASSWORD>' -d LAB.local -ns <DC_IP> -c Group
Local admin rights
bloodhound-python -u 'labuser' -p '<REDACTED_PASSWORD>' -d LAB.local -ns <DC_IP> -c LocalAdmin
ACLs / delegated permissions
bloodhound-python -u 'labuser' -p '<REDACTED_PASSWORD>' -d LAB.local -ns <DC_IP> -c ACL
Object properties
bloodhound-python -u 'labuser' -p '<REDACTED_PASSWORD>' -d LAB.local -ns <DC_IP> -c ObjectProps
DCOM / PSRemote / RDP rights
bloodhound-python -u 'labuser' -p '<REDACTED_PASSWORD>' -d LAB.local -ns <DC_IP> -c DCOM,PSRemote,RDP
Best Practical Command

This is the one I’d remember first for lab / exam workflow:

bloodhound-python -u 'labuser' -p '<REDACTED_PASSWORD>' -d LAB.local -ns <DC_IP> -c All
If You Want Domain Controller by Hostname

If DNS works correctly in the lab:

bloodhound-python -u 'labuser' -p '<REDACTED_PASSWORD>' -d LAB.local -dc dc01.LAB.local -c All
